<DOC><DOCNO> AP880309-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-88 1236EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BytheNumbers     03-09 0237</FIRST><SECOND>AM-By the Numbers,220</SECOND><NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE><HEAD>Population Group Publishes Statistical Look at America</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Population growth puts pressure on theenvironment and resources, whether it occurs in the Third World orthe United States, a population group says in a new booklet.   ``USA by Numbers: A Statistical Portrait of the United States,''was issued Wednesday by Zero Population Growth to show howincreasing numbers of people affect the nation's environment,economy and society as a whole.   ``Although Americans are increasingly aware of populationpressures in other parts of the world, many of us do not recognizethe symptoms of overpopulation when we find them in our ownbackyards,'' said Susan Weber, executive director of the non-profitpopulation group.   The group has compiled statistics from a variety of sources,many of which also appear in the massive Statistical Abstract ofthe United States issued annually by the Commerce Department.   The new 164-page volume, however, concentrates on therelationship between population and the quality of life in thenation.   Chapters in the volume look at population growth over time, cityand rural relationships, young and old, fertility and health,sexuality and abortion, unemployment, poverty, water use,pollution, land use and habitat.   The paperback volume costs $8.95 plus $1.50 for shipping andhandling and can be purchased from Zero Population Growth, 1601Connecticut Ave., N.W., Washington, D.C., 20009.</TEXT></DOC>